Have you ever tried smoking lobster tails? Well, when you have 2 jumbo lobster tails from @lobsteranywhere they must get a smoke bath before making their way to my mouth. I hope you enjoy this recipe as much as I do. 

Ingredients:
2 Jumbo Lobster Tails 8-10 oz
1 Tbsp olive oil
1-2 Tbsp @dizzypigbbq Dizzy Dust
1 stick salted butter, melted

Directions:
Preheat your @biggreenegg to 275°F setup for indirect cooking. I used 2 chunks of apple wood for this cook. While the Big Green Egg preheats prep your lobster tails. Remove the little tiny legs of the lobster for better presentation. Split the shell down the middle and pull out the lobster meat setting it on top of the shell. Use olive oil as a binder for the dry rub. When ready place the tails in the Big Green Egg and let smoke for 45 minutes to 1-hour or until the internal temperature measures 145°F. Place a stick of salted butter in a cast iron dish and smoke it with the lobster for smokey, buttery, deliciousness. When the monster is don, remove, and service with the melted butter and lemon.

Marinade Ingredients:

Kosher salt

Directions:
Blend together marinade ingredients and pour over the flank steak. Place in fridge for 5 hours. Preheat your @biggreenegg to 550° F setup for raised direct grilling. Are you ready for the new year and some new recipes from The BBQ Buddha?! Well, this one features @lobasteranywhere U15 wild caught shrimp cooked in this creamy deliciousness? Let’s see what I did below… 

Ingredients:
2 Tbsp extra-virgin olive oil
1-pound shrimp, peeled, deveined, and tails removed
Kosher salt
Freshly ground black pepper
3 Tbsp butter
5 cloves garlic, minced
1 cup cherry tomatoes, halved
3 cups baby spinach
1/2 cup heavy cream
1/4 cup grated Parmesan
1/4 cup basil, thinly sliced

Directions:
Set up your @biggreenegg for raised direct cooking preheated to 400°F. Place a cast iron pan in to the Big Green Egg and let it preheat. Season the shrimp with kosher salt and black pepper. When ready add the olive oil then the seasoned shrimp to the hot cast iron pan. Sear the shrimp about 2 minutes, then flip until opaque. Remove from cast iron pan and set aside. Add the butter to the cast iron pan. When butter has melted, stir in garlic and cook about 1 minute. Next add the cherry tomatoes and season with salt and pepper. Cook until a few minutes then add spinach and cook until spinach is beginning to wilt. Stir in heavy cream, Parmesan and basil and bring mixture to a simmer. Cook for 2-3 minutes then add the shrimp and stir to combine. Cook 1-2 minutes then remove from the Big Green Egg and serve!

Are you looking for the perfect appetizer for your next party? Well, this bavette steak crostini is the perfect choice. I made this for a holiday party last month and it was a huge hit. Featuring @snakeriverfarms American Wagyu Beef, this recipe is a keeper. 

Ingredients:
1.5 pound bavette steak 
3/4 cup + 1 Tbsp olive oil 
1 Tbsp @dizzypigbbq Red Eye Express 
1 French baguette, sliced in to 1/4” rounds
1 Tbsp Salt, Pepper, Garlic seasoning 
1 5.2oz Boursin Cheese Shallot & Chive
1 container cherry perserve 
1 Tbsp chives, chopped fine

Directions:
Set up your @biggreenegg for raised direct cooking preheated to 350°F. While the BGE is heating prep your French bread by slicing it in to 1/4” rounds. Top the bread with a schmear of olive oil and some SPG. Place the bread on the Big Green Egg and cook for 1-2 minutes per side until nice and toasted. Remove and set to the side. Increase temperature of the BGE to 500°F and when ready place the seasoned bavette steak on the grill grate. Cook 5-6 minutes per side until the internal temperature measures 125°F. Remove and rest 15-20 minutes before slicing against the grain in to bite sized pieces. While the steak rests divide the Boursin cheese across the toasted crostini. The add 1 tsp of cherry preserve to each crostini. Next add a slice of the bavette steak to each crostini. Finally, top the crostini with chopped chives and serve immediately.

How bad do you want one of these grilled scallop and elote street tacos?! Well, this taco featuring @lobsteranywhere sea scallops grilled on my @biggreenegg will be your new favorite taco. Definitely book mark this recipe for your next taco night!

Ingredients:
1 pound U10 Sea Scallops
2 ears of corn
1 Tbsp olive oil
2 tsp @dizzypigbbq SPG
1 jalapeño pepper, de-seeded and diced 
2 Tbsp mayonnaise 
1 Tbsp sour cream
2 Tbsp cojita cheese
1/2 lime, juiced
Cilantro
Pickled red onion
Fresno chili, de-seed and sliced

Directions:
Set up your @biggreenegg for direct cooking preheated to 450°F. Rub the corn with olive oil and SPG seasoning. Grill the corn direct for 4-5 minutes per side until charred. Remove and let cool. When cooled remove the kernels with a knife and place into a bowl with the mayo, sour cream, jalapeño, cojita, and lime juice. Mix well and set to the side. Season the scallops with SPG seasoning and grill direct 3-4 minutes per side until nicely browned. Remove and assemble the tacos. Garnish with pickled red onion, cilantro, Fresno chili, and some @darksideofthegrill hot sauce!

Want to make a perfectly roasted chicken? Well, this method works great every time! Here is what I did…

Ingredients:
1 4-5 pound chicken
Kosher salt
Olive oil

Directions:
The secret is prepping the chicken the day before you plan to cook it. Spatchcock your chicken and season with kosher salt front and back. Place the chicken on a wire rack nestled in a baking pan. Place the pan in the fridge uncovered overnight. The next day the chicken will look funky, but that is because the moisture has been drawn out of the skin. Set up your @biggreenegg for indirect cooking preheated to 375°F. Place a cast iron pan in with your BGE while it is preheating. When ready, place the bird in skin side down and cook for 30 minutes until the skin is nicely browned and crispy. Flip the bird and cook another 30 minutes or until the internal temperature measures 165°F measured in the breast. Remove the pan, take the bird out of the pan and rest 10 minutes before slicing and serving.

Do you love bacon? Well, this recipe for billionaire bacon is beyond delicious. Lots of sweet balanced by some nice heat will make your tastebuds sing! Let’s see what I did below…

Ingredients:
1.5 lbs. @snakeriverfarms Kurobuta Bacon
1 cup granulated sugar
1 cup light brown sugar
1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
1/2 teaspoon @dizzypigbbq Ghost Spice
 
Directions:
Preheat the oven to 375˚F. Wrap a baking sheet tightly with aluminum foil. Place a wire cooling rack on top of the foil wrapped sheet tray. Next, in a large container, mix the sugar, brown sugar, black pepper, and the ghost chili seasoning with a fork until well blended. Dredge each slice of bacon in the sugar mixture, pressing to coat and then shake off excess sugar mixture. Repeat with all bacon slices. Lay the bacon on the wire rack and bake 20 to 30 minutes until crisp.

Ingredients:
1 rack baby back ribs
Yellow Mustard
BBQ Rub

Directions:
Preheat your @biggreenegg to 250°F setup for indirect cooking with 3 chunks of your favorite smoking wood. How egg cited are you for my new book to come out this April? Well, this recipe for Chile Relleno Casserole is one of a hundred recipes in the book! I may have slightly overcooked the top of this for this Reel… but it was still delicious. Here is what I did…

Ingredients
1-pound poblano peppers
12 oz bag of spinach (cooked, and squeezed dry) 
8 oz shredded monetary jack cheese  
8 oz shredded sharp cheddar cheese
1 ear of corn on the cob 
½ cup fresh cilantro, chopped
2 Eggs  
2 Tbsp flour 
¼ tsp kosher salt
¼ tsp baking soda
 
Directions
Before assembling the casserole, you need to roast the vegetables first. To do that, preheat your @biggreenegg to 400°F setup for direct grilling. When the Big Green Egg is ready roast the corn first by placing directly on the grill great and cook turning frequently until nicely browned 6-8 minutes. Pull the corn off the grill grate and set to the side to cool. Now roast the poblano peppers until the skin is blackened and blistered. Place the roasted peppers in a covered container so the steam helps loosen the skin. Next, peel and deseed the peppers. Set to the side and move to the next step. Place the convEGGtor in your Big Green Egg so that it is now setup for indirect cooking. Set the temperature to 475°F. Now prepare the casserole. First, make the batter by whisking two egg whites until foamy then add in 1 egg yolk, the flour, kosher salt, and baking soda. Mix this together to form the batter. Set this to the side until your casserole is assembled. Place a layer of roasted chilis (split open like a book) on the bottom of a casserole dish. Now top the chilis with the spinach and a mixture of the cheeses. Place another layer of the chilis on top of that and cover with the roasted corn, cilantro, and more of the cheeses. Finally, add one last layer of chilis, the remaining cheeses, and top that with the batter. Place the casserole in the preheated Big Green Egg and cook until the cheesy topping is nicely browned and bubbling around the edges. Remove the casserole and let rest for 15-20 minutes before serving.

Have you ever used red wine in your steak marinade? Well, for this marinade I reduced a big fat cabernet sauvignon helping to develop deep flavors that accentuate the grilled beef. You are going to love this recipe so much… thank me later!
 
Ingredients
1 cup soy sauce
1 cup white sugar
1 cup water
2 cups Cabernet Sauvignon 
½ cup gochujang
2.5 Lbs. flank steak
Salt and pepper
3 green onions, sliced thinly (reserve some of the green parts for garnish)
Toasted sesame seeds for garnish
 
Directions
In a small saucepan, heat the red wine over medium high heat until reduced to ¼ cup. This should to 20 minutes or so. In a separate small saucepan, whisk together soy sauce, sugar, and water. Heat the mixture over medium high heat, bring to a boil, remove from heat, cool, mix with gochujang, and set aside. Next, add the reduced wine to the soy sauce mixture you set aside earlier and mix well. Let the marinade cool, then pour over the flank steak in a resealable plastic bag, and most of the sliced green onions, and refrigerate overnight. Pull the flank steak out of the marinade and let come to room temperature as you get the @biggreenegg ready for direct grilling with the temperature set to 500°F. Sear the flank steak for 5 minutes each side. Once your steak reaches 125°F pull and let rest 20 minutes before slicing and serving. Slice against the grain and serve with toasted sesame seeds and green onion on top.

Have you made stuffed chicken breasts on your @biggreenegg before? Well, this recipe for Stuffed Chicken Florentine is another one from my new book The Ultimate Big Green Egg Cookbook set to be released April 2023. Pre-orders are available now… link in my bio. 
 
Let’s see what I did below… 
 
Ingredients
4 boneless skinless chicken breasts (about 1 1/2 lb.)
@dizzypigbbq Wonder Bird
6 oz cream cheese, softened
1 Tbsp mayonnaise
¼ cup Federalist Chardonnay 
2 garlic cloves, minced
¼ tsp kosher salt 
2 cups baby spinach leaves, chopped
½ cup shredded mozzarella cheese
½ cup shredded parmesan cheese
 
Directions
Preheat your Big Green Egg to 350°F setup for 2-zone grilling i.e., direct side and an indirect side. While the Big Green Egg is preheating, make the Florentine stuffing by combining all the ingredients in a bowl. Next, make a slice on the side of each chicken breast and fold open creating a pocket. Divide the Florentine stuffing into 4 equal portions. Now gently stuff each chicken breast with the Florentine stuffing. Use wooden toothpicks to close and seal the pockets. Ingredients:
1-pound salmon filet
2 tsp paprika
1 tsp garlic powder

Directions

When the Big Green Egg and perforated pan are preheated add some oil to the perforated pan so that the entire surface is coated in oil. Add the sliced pineapple rings to the grill grate and cook next to the salmon. When your fish measures 145°F using an instant read thermometer, pull the blackened filet off and rest on a cutting board for a few minutes. Remove the charred pineapple, dice, and place in a bowl. Next, mix the charred pineapple with the jalapeño, red bell pepper, red onion, lime juice, cilantro, and season to taste with kosher salt. Once the chicken temperature is between 155-160°F baste with the Korean glaze. Flip, baste with the glaze, and continue cooking until the chicken is between 170-175°F. Remove the chicken, rest for 10 minutes, before serving. Garnish with green onion and chopped peanuts.

Ingredients:
2 racks of baby ribs
Yellow mustard
BBQ rub
50/50 mix apple juice and 
1 cup Federalist Lodi Zinfandel Red Wine
1 ½ cups ketchup
¼ cup brown sugar
1 Tbsp apple cider vinegar
1 Tbsp tomato paste
1 Tbsp Worcestershire sauce

1 tsp onion powder
½ tsp garlic powder
½ tsp paprika
½ tsp dry mustard

Directions:
Setup your smoker for indirect cooking at 250°F using hickory wood chunks for smoke flavor. Prep your baby back ribs by removing the membrane, slathering with yellow mustard, and covering with your favorite BBQ rub. Place the ribs in the smoker and cook for 2 hours before checking on them. Now fold in the red wine reduction, mix thoroughly and simmer for an additional 10 minutes. Continue smoking the ribs for a total of 4 1/2 hours then glaze the ribs with the red wine BBQ sauce. Do you want an amazing bite of steak? Well, this American Wagyu NY Manhattan Roast with homemade cowboy butter just may be the best bite you’ll ever have! This would make for the perfect centerpiece for your holiday meal 🥘 

Ingredients
3 pound @snakeriverfarms NY Manhattan Roast
2 Tbsp @dizzypigbbq Raising the Steaks
6 Tbsp butter, softened
Juice and zest of half a lemon
4 cloves garlic, minced
1 Tbsp Dijon mustard
Pinch of cayenne pepper
1/4 tsp paprika
2 Tbsp fresh chopped parsley
1 Tbsp freshly chopped chives
2 tsp minced thyme
1/4 tap red pepper flakes
Salt and freshly ground black pepper

Directions
In a small bowl, combine softened butter, lemon juice, garlic, mustard, cayenne, and paprika. Whisk the sauce to combine. Stir in parsley, chives, red pepper, and thyme and season with salt and pepper. Roll up in plastic wrap and pace in fridge for at least an hour. Want some of this Bloody Mary braised Chuck roast? Well, this recipe from my new book features a @snakeriverfarms American Wagyu chuck roast for amazing flavor!

Ingredients
3-pound @snakeriverfarms Chuck Roast
2-8oz cans Zing Zang Bloody Mary Cocktail Mix
4 cups beef stock
2 carrots, peeled and diced
2 rib celery medium diced
1 yellow onion, diced
5 cloves garlic, minced
2 bay leaves
2 Tbs @biggreenegg Signature Steakhouse seasoning
2 Tbs olive oil
 
Directions
Preheat your Big Green Egg to 250°F setup for indirect cooking. Place 2-3 chunks of smoking wood in with the burning coals. Next, Remove the chuck roast from the packaging, apply @fyrstarter Gold as a binder, and season liberally with Signature Steakhouse seasoning from big Green Egg.  When the Big Green Egg is preheated place your chuck roast inside and let smoke for 3 hours undisturbed. While the roast is smoking, prepare the rest of your ingredients for the braise. After 3-hours, remove the roast, and let rest while you make the braise. Preheat your oven to 350°F and place a cast iron Dutch oven on your stovetop set to medium heat. When preheated add the olive oil to the Dutch oven then the onion, carrots, and celery. Let the vegetables cook while stirring occasionally for 2-3 minutes until soft. Add the chopped garlic and cook another 1-2 minute until fragrant. Next, deglaze the Dutch oven with the Bloody Mary mix then add in the beef stock. Bring to a boil and then add the smoked chuck roast. Cover and place the Dutch oven in the preheated oven for 2-hours. After the 2-hours take the Dutch oven out of the oven, remove the bay leaves, and place the chuck roast on a cutting board. Remove the ½ of the vegetables with a slotted spoon and add them with a little of the braising liquid to a blender and pulse blend until you form a thick puree. Add the back in to the braising liquid and mix to thicken. Chop up the chuck roast and add that back in to the braising liquid. Moix together and serve over wide egg noodles. Enjoy!

Well, I was very inspired by the food in Thailand and have been working in the background to learn this way of cooking. This dish is named Pad Kra Pao and I made it with @snakeriverfarms ground kurabuta pork. The flavors in this dish are amazing. Let’s see what I did below…
 
 
Ingredients:
2 tablespoon fish sauce
2 tablespoon light soy sauce
2 tablespoon sweet soy sauce
2 tablespoon oyster sauce
8 tablespoons water
11 ounces fresh green beans chopped into small lengths (1 to 2 inches)
6 small red chilis de-seeded and chopped finely
8 garlic cloves crushed or chopped finely
14 ounces minced pork or chicken, turkey, beef!
1 bunch fresh basil 
Plain rice 
 
Instructions: 
Mix together the fish sauce, soy sauce, sweet soy sauce, oyster sauce and water in a bowl or jug and set aside. Preheat your @biggreenegg to 400°F setup for direct grilling with the EGGspander base in place. Heat up a large drizzle of oil in your carbon steel wok. Then stir-fry the green beans for a few minutes. Next, add the chopped chilis and garlic and stir-fry for a couple more minutes. Add the pork and break up with your wooden spoon. Stir-fry until cooked about 5 more minutes mixing the ingredients constantly. Pour in the sauce, mix well, then let it bubble for a minute or two more. Stir in the basil until wilted, then serve with the rice and enjoy!

Are you looking for the perfect comfort food dish to keep you warm? I found this recipe on the @snakeriverfarms site and put my own spin on it using my @biggreenegg Large. Let’s see how I made this dish below…
 
Ingredients:
4 pounds @snakeriverfarms short ribs, cut into 2- or 3-inch pieces
1 tablespoon vegetable oil
2 tablespoons tomato paste
2/3 cup diced yellow onions
2 teaspoons minced garlic
1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme
2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
1/2 cup dark beer, such as Guinness
1 1/2 cups beef broth
2 bay leaves
Creamy polenta, for serving
 
Directions:
Cut the beef short ribs in-between the bones in to 6 separate cubes. Dress the short ribs using @fyrstarter Gold as a binder and @biggreenegg SPG for the seasoning. Preheat Big Green Egg to 250°F setup for indirect cooking using hickory chunks for your smoke flavor. When the Big Green Egg is preheated and stable, place the seasoned ribs inside and smoke the short ribs for 2 hours. Remove the ribs and bring them inside. Place a large Dutch oven over medium heat then add the vegetable oil. Add the onions and garlic first and cook 2-3 minutes until soft and fragrant. Next add the tomato paste, thyme, bay leaves and cook, stirring, until the tomato paste begins to caramelize, about 3 minutes. Sprinkle in the flour and cook, stirring, for another 1 minute. Add the beer to deglaze the pot and use a wooden spoon to scrape up any brown bits. Preheat the oven to 325°F. Return the short ribs (and any juices) to the pot then add the beef broth. Bring the mixture to a simmer then cover it and place it in the oven to braise until the beef is tender and pulling apart from the bone, 2 to 2 1/2 hours. Serve the short ribs over creamy polenta.
